<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Deinandra fasciculata </i>is a late-flowering summer annual that germinates in the spring, not winter, and blooms and fruits after many of the spring annuals have gone to seed. Plants tend to occur in heavy or poorly drained soils. <i>Deinandra </i>is one of six genera segregated from <i>Hemizonia, </i>and some species are perennials (Baldwin 2000). These genera are adapted particularly to seasonal climates in western North America. <br/>
<br/>
Klein and Evens (2005) considered some stands close to <i>Amsinckia</i> (<i>menziesii, tessellata</i>) and other upland herb alliances and other stands close to <i>Centromadia</i> (<i>pungens</i>) and other vernal pool alliances. Barbour et al. (2007b) suggested that <i>D. fasciculata </i>was an indicator of southern California vernal pools, but their stands were less alkaline and contained few halophytes. We need further sampling and analysis to understand the herbaceous vegetation and vernal pool patterns involving <i>Amsinckia menziesii, Brodiaea orcuttii, Centromadia </i>spp., <i>Deinandra fasciculata, Eryngium aristulatum </i>var. <i>parishii, Orcuttia californica, </i>and <i>Pogogyne abramsii </i>in southern California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
