    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Deinandra fasciculata</i> includes Central California Coast (261A), Central California Coast Ranges (M262A), and Southern California Coast (261B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf, Bk-l). In San Diego Co., stands occur along edges of vernal pools (Bauder 2000). In western Riverside Co., an association containing <i>Hordeum depressum </i>and <i>Atriplex coronata var. notatior </i>occurs at low to moderate cover typically on vernal alkali plains or surrounding clay-rich vernal pools (Klein and Evens 2005). Another association containing an assortment of natives and non-natives occupies clay flats. <i>D. fasciculata </i>also occurs as an understory plant in many upland coastal scrub types.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Although the full extent of the alliance is unknown, associations as currently defined are limited in extent, occurring in naturally rare vernal pool and flat alkaline settings. Many of these sites have been impacted by agriculture, clearing, development, and non-native plants, especially in southern California. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
